nt-garde integrale' -- t14. From Science to the Marvellous. The Illusion of Movement, Between Chronophotography and Contemporary Cinema -- tSection 3: Shop Windows Of Filmed Ideas, Events, Types, Objects -- tChronology -- tFilmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFuturism and early cinema shared a fascination with dynamic movement and speed, presenting both as harbingers of an emerging new way of life and new aesthetic criteria. And the Futurists quickly latched on to cinema as a device with great potential to manipulate our perceptions in order to create a new world. In the edited collection Futurist Cinema, Rossella Catanese explores that conjunction, bringing in avant-garde artists and their manifestos to show how painters and other artists turned to cinema as a model for overcoming the inherently static nature of painting in order to rethink it for a new era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics)zItalyxHistory. 0aFuturism (Art)zItalyxHistory. 0aMotion pictureszItalyxHistory. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh  aFuturism, Cinema, Film Studies, Avant-garde.1 aBertetto, Paolo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarpi, Giancarlo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCastrillo, Carolina Fernández, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatanese, Rossella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCatanese, Rossella, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLista, Giovanni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLotti, Denis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular